Choosing compute, the four-scenario cheat sheet.

The exam is scenario-driven. It hands you a workload and asks which compute fits. Here's the cheat sheet.

For interactive development and ad-hoc exploration in notebooks, use an all-purpose cluster. It stays up, multiple people can share it, and you can rerun cells as you iterate.

For scheduled, automated production pipelines, use a job cluster. It spins up per run, it's isolated, it tears down when done, and it bills at the cheaper job rate.

For business intelligence dashboards and ad-hoc sequel, or connecting business intelligence tools, use a sequel warehouse. Prefer serverless, for the fastest start and the best price and performance.

For bursty or unpredictable work, or when you simply don't want to manage infrastructure, use serverless compute. It starts in seconds, autoscales, and has no idle cost.

One more comes up often: machine learning training runs on an all-purpose or job cluster using the machine learning runtime, which bundles the machine learning libraries and can use G-P-Us.

The throughline is to match the shape of the work to the compute. Interactive and shared goes to all-purpose. Scheduled and isolated goes to a job cluster. Sequel and business intelligence go to a warehouse. Spiky and hands-off goes to serverless.
